T1  - The Role of Dispute Settlement Procedures in International Trade Agreements*
PY  - 2011
Y1  - 2011/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjq005
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 126
IS  - 1
SP  - 475
EP  - 515
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  -  Although disputes are typically treated as synonymous with concerns about enforcement in economic models of trade agreements, in reality most WTO disputes seem to concern the interpretation of vague provisions, or instances where the agreement is silent. And some have suggested that the WTO's Dispute Settlement Body (DSB) could usefully grant exceptions to rigid contractual obligations. These activist DSB roles could help “complete” an incomplete contract. But how activist should the DSB be? Should DSB rulings set precedent? We address these questions by characterizing the optimal choice of contract form and DSB mandate under various contracting conditions. JEL Codes: D02, D78, D86, F13, K12, K33. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjq005
ER  - 



